segments.text: Long hours?
Yeah, long hours.
And so the first thing you do is analyze as to whether or not you really want to be a leader.
It's a lot easier to be in the background, because if you're on the front line, everybody's looking at you.
A lot more demanding.
And it's a lot more demanding.
And there's a lot more pressure on you.
So the question is, can you stand the pressure?
or you're going to get ulcers over it.
And I found that a lot of people were just made poor commanders.
In fact, Napoleon, I think, said that there are no bad regiments, there are only bad colonels.
The second, okay, the first thing is if you want to be a leader, okay, there's one.
I'll tell you the next thing is,
decide what job you want.
Then make a study of that particular job as to what qualifications the individual who has a job has and draw yourself up an educational plan, a job plan to be qualified to take that job.
Go out and get the training or the education that's necessary.
Education and whatever, if it's a
And I would say that almost any leader needs to be able to be an accountant type.
An accountant type.
What does that mean?
Well, I don't mean an accountant type.
He needs to have the ability to keep the books or look at a financial statement and be able to analyze a financial statement.
and to be able to analyze financial data.
I think in the building business, had I not been a professional bookkeeper or accountant, I would have been lost if you had to depend on somebody else to keep the books.
Because in the early stages of any company, why the critical
item is your finances.
And you have to be on top of it on a day-to-day basis.
So you just have to, as far as I'm concerned, you have to be a bookkeeper of some sort to, in regards of what job you are.
Almost all the students that we are sponsoring down at Texas A&M, I recommend it's somewhere along the line.
one or two of their electives be an accountant so that they know how to keep books and be able to analyze whether or not they're making a profit.
Even if they're working for somebody else, why should they be able to find out if they themselves are making a profit?
And the other thing that has done me the most good is being a typist.
I learned typing early and I figured I got my poem at the west point by typing letters.
All my research and books and things of this sort, I typed it out.
I'll agree that now your copying machine has come into the being where for five cents you can put a book and get a copy of a page that you particularly want and file it away.
then why it was a matter of typing these jewels that you ran across in books.
I think that's along with the other qualifications of enthusiasm and with imagination, willing to work night and day to
to reach your goal, I think that's it.
Okay.
There's another thing that you said during our interview, I think it might have been yesterday, that I was interested in, the last thing that I'd like to talk about as far as leadership is concerned.
You said that you have to be willing to rock the boat.
Now, I've heard a lot of people say about the military, well, it's a guy that gets ahead who doesn't rock the boat, he just fits in and
just takes the orders and carries them out.
And you're telling me that you have to be able to rock the boat.
Would you explain that?

Well, you're... Well, if you... Well, it's the same thing as whether or not you're rocking a boat or create waves or... As far as I'm concerned, if you're going to be a commander, why, you have to be willing to...
look at a situation and if it requires changing why get it changed.
And I'll agree that when you rock the boat you come to somebody's attention.
And if you don't rock the boat why then
might get a good efficiency report, but sooner or later, as far as I'm concerned, you're going to be found out.
Because I used to write efficiency reports on, when I was in the National Security Agency, we used to have some members of there that I had to write
efficiency reports on.

Well, the guys that didn't rock the boat, well, you just said, well, you hadn't heard anything good about him, you hadn't heard anything bad about him, so you rate him probably above average because he had been selected as, but if he had been rocking the boat, well, then he comes to attention, so you knew what he was doing.
Now, maybe if you didn't like what he was doing, well, maybe you'd rate him down a little bit, but I just think that
In other words, when you rock the boat in the military, you should make your ways, but you should be pretty sure that you're on the right path.
On the right track, yeah.
Because if you rock the boat and you're not on the right path, then you could be in trouble.
Is this part of the creativity aspect then?
Well, I think the... Coming up with ideas?
Creativity is to come up with ideas, and actually you get your ideas from
reading magazines, reading books, collecting documents.
And then when you need to, well, I think this is education.
I think you're really, education is the, you are educating yourself not to have something stored in your brain, but where you can find it.
And this is the reason that I've collected such an extensive
file on how to be a success, how to be a failure.
This, if I want to review how to be a success or the value of reading, you just go to a file, pick out all of these articles that have been written on it, and refresh yourself.
And I used to take vile speeches.
which is a very good magazine on the good speeches and of the week.
I think it's almost a weekly magazine.
It was a weekly and maybe a monthly now.
And I used to take that and there's always someone made a speech that really put words in the right
contacts that you liked and it fits in right with your idea so you just tear it out and put it in a file someplace.
But I think if you're out in front you just can't be a non-entity as a commander.
You just have to be willing to, as you say, rock the boat and everybody will... Make those decisions.
It'll attract the attention of both the people above, and it'll also attract all the attention of the people below.
Well, during this interview, we've talked about your early years, your education, both at A&M, and compared that with West Point, your military career, your ideas on leadership.
There must be something else that... Is there anything else that we've left?
I'm sure that in every man's life, there's a lot of things that you leave out that are important to the development of a general officer, but is there anything that you'd just like to
to talk on before we close because I'm out of questions.
Well I'm out of talking I think.
Okay.
Well thank you very much General Hetherington for this.
I know Texas A&M, the former students and I really appreciate it.
